Sync Local Repo with Remote
➤ Reset local branch to match remote exactly
git fetch origin
git reset --hard origin/main

What it does:

fetch → gets latest changes
reset --hard → wipes your local changes and matches remote

Use when: your local repo is messed up and you want a clean state.

Examples:

You broke your code → just reset to remote
Merge conflicts everywhere → nuke local and sync fresh
🧹 2. Remove File from Git Tracking (but keep locally)
➤ Remove .env from Git
git rm --cached backend/.env

What it does:
Stops tracking the file but doesn’t delete it from your system.

Important: Add to .gitignore after this.

Examples:

You accidentally committed secrets
You want .env to stay local only
⏪ 3. Undo Commits
➤ Remove last commit completely
git reset --hard HEAD~1

What it does:
Deletes last commit + changes (permanently).

Examples:

You committed broken code
You committed sensitive data
➤ Push rewritten history (DANGEROUS)
git push origin main --force

What it does:
Overwrites remote history with your local version.

Reality check:
If others are working on the branch, this can wreck their work.

Examples:

You removed secrets and need to overwrite history
You cleaned up commits locally
🌿 4. Branch Management
➤ Create and switch to a branch from remote
git switch -c master origin/master

What it does:
Creates local master tracking origin/master.

Examples:

You cloned repo and need to work on master
You want to track a remote branch locally
➤ Delete remote branch
git push origin --delete branch_name

What it does:
Deletes branch from remote repo.

Examples:

Feature branch is merged
Cleanup old branches
🔄 5. Pull with Rebase
➤ Rebase local changes on top of remote
git pull --rebase origin develop

What it does:

Pulls latest develop
Re-applies your commits on top (clean history)

Why it matters:
Avoids messy merge commits.

Examples:

You want a linear commit history
You’re working on feature branch and syncing with develop
⚠️ Brutal Reality (Don’t Ignore This)

You’re using destructive commands heavily:

reset --hard
push --force

These are not beginner-safe.

Two common ways people screw this up:
Deleting work permanently
Example: reset --hard → no recovery unless in reflog
Breaking team workflow
Example: push --force → others' commits disappear
🧠 Minimal Mental Model (Memorize This)
fetch → download
pull → download + merge/rebase
reset --hard → destroy local changes
push --force → overwrite remote
rm --cached → stop tracking file
switch -c → create new branch